SIMPLE: winnow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Winnow
<hw>Win"now</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧n"n⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Winnowed</conjf>
<pr>(w⟦icr⟧n"n⟦osl⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Winnowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>windewen</ets>,
<ets>winewen</ets>, AS. <ets>windwian</ets>; akin to Goth.
<ets>winpjan</ets> (in comp.), <ets>winpi</ets>-skauro a fan, L.
<ets>ventilare</ets> to fan, to winnow; cf. L. <ets>wannus</ets> a fan
for winnowing, G. <ets>wanne</ets>, OHG. <ets>wanna</ets>. ⟦root⟧131.
See <er>Wind</er> moving air, and cf. <er>Fan</er>., <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Ventilate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate, and drive off, the chaff from by means
of wind; to fan; <as>as, to <ex>winnow</ex> grain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ho <qex>winnoweth</qex> barley to-night in the threshing
floor.</q> <rj><qau>Ruth. iii. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sift, as for the purpose of separating falsehood
from truth; to separate, as bad from good.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Winnow</qex> well this thought, and you shall find⟦br⟧
This light as chaff that flies before the wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To beat with wings, or as with
wings.</def><mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now on the polar winds; then with quick fan⟦br⟧
<qex>Winnows</qex> the buxom air.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winnow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Winnow
<hw>Win"now</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To separate chaff
from grain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Winnow</qex> not with every wind.</q> <rj><qau>Ecclus. v.
9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winnower</ent>⟦br⟧
